00:31:13,750 --> 00:31:15,946
He broke It down
and put It in the bag.

268
00:31:15,970 --> 00:31:16,826
Obviously.

269
00:31:16,850 --> 00:31:20,350
Can we get dimensions, please?

270
00:31:25,820 --> 00:31:28,336
The bag is less than
60 centimeters tall.

271
00:31:28,360 --> 00:31:29,096
So?

272
00:31:29,120 --> 00:31:32,087
The Tac-50 barrel
is 737 millimeters and

273
00:31:32,088 --> 00:31:35,588
It's the shortest
around in this category.

274
00:31:36,040 --> 00:31:37,716
4 meters long.

275
00:31:37,740 --> 00:31:39,316
The rifle's not in the bag.

276
00:31:39,340 --> 00:31:41,756
If It was in the bag,
we'D see the barrel poking out.

277
00:31:41,780 --> 00:31:43,676
He left It behind.

278
00:31:43,700 --> 00:31:46,256
No. Forensics found no
trace of a weapon at the scene.

279
00:31:46,280 --> 00:31:48,865
When a sniper finds a rifle,
one that

280
00:31:48,866 --> 00:31:51,356
allows him to make a
shot at that distance,

281
00:31:51,380 --> 00:31:53,336
that rifle is a keeper.

282
00:31:53,360 --> 00:31:55,756
He's never going to leave It behind.

283
00:31:55,780 --> 00:31:57,576
Which means he took It with him.

284
00:31:57,600 --> 00:32:00,376
And if he took It with him,
then It has to be in that bag.

285
00:32:00,400 --> 00:32:03,900
I'm not following Bianca.

286
00:32:03,940 --> 00:32:06,476
You said the bag isn't big enough.

287
00:32:06,500 --> 00:32:09,676
Which means the
rifle is bespoke.

288
00:32:09,700 --> 00:32:11,616
The barrel came in two parts.

289
00:32:11,640 --> 00:32:15,760
A barrel in two parts is
the gunmaker's holy grail.

290
00:32:16,400 --> 00:32:18,856
If the rifling were
out the tiniest fraction,

291
00:32:18,880 --> 00:32:20,216
It would compromise the shot.

292
00:32:20,240 --> 00:32:21,276
It's impossible.

293
00:32:21,300 --> 00:32:24,156
There's a gunmaker who's
been trying to do this for years.

294
00:32:24,180 --> 00:32:27,680
His name is Norman Stoke.

295
00:32:28,000 --> 00:32:28,882
Is Mr.

296
00:32:28,883 --> 00:32:30,996
Stoke British?

297
00:32:31,020 --> 00:32:33,356
Northern Irish.

298
00:32:33,380 --> 00:32:34,396
Well,

299
00:32:34,420 --> 00:32:37,496
I suppose they count
as British for now.

300
00:32:37,520 --> 00:32:39,356
Do we know where Mr. Stoke is?

301
00:32:39,380 --> 00:32:41,296
Can we get a special
branch to scoop him up?

302
00:32:41,320 --> 00:32:44,376
He's been on the run since the
Stockholm assassination in 2018.

303
00:32:44,400 --> 00:32:45,416
How unfortunate.

304
00:32:45,440 --> 00:32:47,876
But I have an asset.

305
00:32:47,900 --> 00:32:49,876
I know I can find him.

306
00:32:49,900 --> 00:32:52,036
What good would that do us?

307
00:32:52,060 --> 00:32:54,496
Oh, well, gunmaker makes gun,

308
00:32:54,520 --> 00:32:56,796
gunmaker sells gun to assassin.

309
00:32:56,820 --> 00:32:58,276
Highly speculative.

310
00:32:58,300 --> 00:32:59,896
It is elite, however.

311
00:32:59,920 --> 00:33:03,420
And to be frank,
we don't have many of those.

312
00:33:18,820 --> 00:33:19,380
Let's go.

313
00:33:19,400 --> 00:33:22,900
I'm going to the Northern Guard.

314
00:33:26,560 --> 00:33:27,196
Bianca,

315
00:33:27,220 --> 00:33:30,720
a moment, please.

316
00:33:44,280 --> 00:33:47,780
It's always flattering when the
Germans come asking for our expertise.

317
00:33:49,860 --> 00:33:51,828
Although It would be
a little embarrassing

318
00:33:51,829 --> 00:33:54,456
if the gunmaker
turns out to be British.

319
00:33:54,480 --> 00:33:57,396
Who exactly is this Norman Stoke?

320
00:33:57,420 --> 00:33:59,460
Stoke started making machine guns

321
00:33:59,461 --> 00:34:03,520
for loyalist paramilitaries
back in the 80s in East Belfast.

322
00:34:03,760 --> 00:34:06,175
Norman and his
brother Larry killed more

323
00:34:06,176 --> 00:34:08,816
than a dozen innocent
Catholic civilians.

324
00:34:08,840 --> 00:34:11,120
Larry was eventually
caught and went to prison

325
00:34:11,121 --> 00:34:13,876
but was released under
the peace agreement.

326
00:34:13,900 --> 00:34:16,636
He's now an enforcer
for a gang of drug dealers.

327
00:34:16,660 --> 00:34:20,875
Norman, meanwhile,
perfected his craft and made

328
00:34:20,876 --> 00:34:23,296
the gun used in the
Stockholm assassination.

329
00:34:23,320 --> 00:34:25,560
How would you go about
finding Norman Stoke?

330
00:34:25,561 --> 00:34:28,636
I have an asset in Belfast.

331
00:34:28,660 --> 00:34:32,160
Code name Sparrow.

332
00:34:33,000 --> 00:34:37,581
I've heard good things about you,
Bianca.

333
00:34:39,940 --> 00:34:42,636
Don't let me down.

334
00:34:42,660 --> 00:34:46,160
Yeah.

335
00:36:25,310 --> 00:36:26,146
Hey.

336
00:36:26,170 --> 00:36:27,526
Hey.

337
00:36:27,550 --> 00:36:30,286
You look like you're at an airport.

338
00:36:30,310 --> 00:36:31,786
Yeah, sorry.

339
00:36:31,810 --> 00:36:33,646
What about parents' evening?

340
00:36:33,670 --> 00:36:36,166
So I'm assuming you're not coming.

341
00:36:36,190 --> 00:36:38,746
It's a last minute thing.

342
00:36:38,770 --> 00:36:41,146
You know, she's really
worked her socks off this term.

343
00:36:41,170 --> 00:36:42,106
I know. I know.

344
00:36:42,130 --> 00:36:43,646
I feel awful about It.

345
00:36:43,670 --> 00:36:45,586
There was nothing I could do.

346
00:36:45,610 --> 00:36:47,246
Well,
you could try telling her yourself.

347
00:36:47,270 --> 00:36:48,950
I can't. I can't.

348
00:36:48,951 --> 00:36:52,470
I've just got to Belfast and
I'm already late for a meeting.

349
00:36:52,670 --> 00:36:54,646
Can you do It, please?

350
00:36:54,670 --> 00:36:58,126
Look, I will try my best
to get on the last flight.

351
00:36:58,150 --> 00:36:58,946
Okay.

352
00:36:58,970 --> 00:36:59,906
I'm sorry.

353
00:36:59,930 --> 00:37:00,906
All right. Bye.

354
00:37:00,930 --> 00:37:04,430
Bye.

355
00:38:55,480 --> 00:38:56,976
When I saw your number,

356
00:38:57,000 --> 00:38:59,556
I almost had a stroke.

357
00:38:59,580 --> 00:39:01,656
I thought I'D seen the last of you.

358
00:39:01,680 --> 00:39:04,956
It has been a long time.

359
00:39:04,980 --> 00:39:08,480
How have you been?

360
00:39:08,660 --> 00:39:10,236
What do you want, Nadine?

361
00:39:10,260 --> 00:39:11,756
House the family.

362
00:39:11,780 --> 00:39:13,876
Leave my family out of It.

363
00:39:13,900 --> 00:39:19,280
If Larry knew who I was talking to,
he'D kill me.

364
00:39:28,520 --> 00:39:30,296
But you're being careful.

365
00:39:30,320 --> 00:39:32,416
You remember the protocols?

366
00:39:32,440 --> 00:39:35,056
Yes. Good.

367
00:39:35,080 --> 00:39:38,580
And there's nothing
for you to worry about.

368
00:39:39,660 --> 00:39:44,841
When was the last time Larry
spoke to his brother, Norman?

369
00:39:45,940 --> 00:39:47,796
Not since he disappeared.

370
00:39:47,820 --> 00:39:51,320
Are you telling me the truth, Alison?

371
00:39:51,560 --> 00:39:55,060
I know the brothers are close
and I need to find Norman now.

372
00:39:56,220 --> 00:39:59,720
Not my problem.

373
00:40:06,500 --> 00:40:10,160
It's very much your problem because
if you don't help me find Norman,

374
00:40:10,880 --> 00:40:13,176
you'll go back to prison.

375
00:40:13,200 --> 00:40:16,490
I'm sorry.

376
00:40:16,491 --> 00:40:18,446
Are you married?

377
00:40:18,470 --> 00:40:20,546
No. Children?

378
00:40:20,570 --> 00:40:22,606
No. Career woman?

379
00:40:22,630 --> 00:40:25,786
It's written all over you.

380
00:40:25,810 --> 00:40:27,246
If you had a husband,

381
00:40:27,270 --> 00:40:29,946
you'D know men
have their little secrets.

382
00:40:29,970 --> 00:40:33,470
Well,
this is a little secret I want in on.

383
00:40:34,050 --> 00:40:36,426
I need you to find
out where Norman is.

384
00:40:36,450 --> 00:40:39,950
Today.

385
00:40:49,290 --> 00:40:51,846
I can't just ask
Larry out of the blue.

386
00:40:51,870 --> 00:40:53,826
He'D be suspicious.

387
00:40:53,850 --> 00:40:57,350
I'D have to work up to It.

388
00:40:57,510 --> 00:40:59,046
You've got my number.

389
00:40:59,070 --> 00:41:02,570
I expect to hear from you tonight.

390
00:41:06,290 --> 00:41:09,790
Can I go alone?

391
00:41:10,370 --> 00:41:13,870
It's a free country.

392
00:42:55,180 --> 00:42:56,696
Alison, It's Nadine.

393
00:42:56,720 --> 00:43:01,801
I haven't heard from you and
I'm very disappointed. Call me.

394
00:43:02,320 --> 00:43:05,820
Nadine?

395
00:43:05,860 --> 00:43:07,976
Oh.

396
00:43:08,000 --> 00:43:11,500
It's in-joke.

397
00:43:11,980 --> 00:43:13,996
Look, baby, I'm so sorry.

398
00:43:14,020 --> 00:43:15,756
You know about parents' evening.

399
00:43:15,780 --> 00:43:19,280
I really am.

400
00:44:58,330 --> 00:45:01,830
Don't turn around.

401
00:45:04,140 --> 00:45:07,296
Did you come alone?

402
00:45:07,320 --> 00:45:12,401
Yes, I followed your
instructions to the letter.

403
00:45:14,440 --> 00:45:17,940
Who's the target?

404
00:45:18,000 --> 00:45:20,176
Ulay Dag Charles.

405
00:45:20,200 --> 00:45:22,196
UDC.

406
00:45:22,220 --> 00:45:25,720
Can you get to him?

407
00:45:29,280 --> 00:45:31,476
It'll cost.

408
00:45:31,500 --> 00:45:35,000
I mentioned a guide
price of ten million dollars.

409
00:45:35,280 --> 00:45:39,881
Multiply that by ten and then
perhaps we can have a conversation.

410
00:45:40,780 --> 00:45:44,256
That's a very expensive conversation.

411
00:45:44,280 --> 00:45:45,376
Half on commission,

412
00:45:45,400 --> 00:45:46,196
half on completion,

413
00:45:46,220 --> 00:45:48,336
all reasonable expenses paid.

414
00:45:48,360 --> 00:45:53,201
Well, I'D have to consult
my colleagues about that.

415
00:45:56,610 --> 00:46:00,110
Hello?

416
00:46:02,430 --> 00:46:03,726
Alison, It's Nadine.

417
00:46:03,750 --> 00:46:05,086
You were supposed
to call me last night.

418
00:46:05,110 --> 00:46:08,610
I need to hear from you.

419
00:46:09,110 --> 00:46:12,146
Uh, get me everything we have
on Alison's daughter, Emma.

420
00:46:12,170 --> 00:46:12,666
Copy.

421
00:46:12,690 --> 00:46:13,226
Yeah?

422
00:46:13,250 --> 00:46:16,750
Yeah, yeah, on It.

423
00:46:19,130 --> 00:46:22,630
The B and D believe.

424
00:46:24,730 --> 00:46:27,990
The B and D believe our
sniper thought he'D find Manfred

425
00:46:27,991 --> 00:46:31,286
at the Fest und Fest Unternehmer
offices the night before.

426
00:46:31,310 --> 00:46:34,810
But Manfred wasn't there,
so he shot his son, Elias.

427
00:46:35,110 --> 00:46:38,306
Manfred was
always the real target.

428
00:46:38,330 --> 00:46:41,830
Elias was used as bait to
lure Manfred to the hospital.

429
00:46:41,970 --> 00:46:43,966
That would take a lot of pre-planning.

430
00:46:43,990 --> 00:46:47,490
Well, all planning is pre...

431
00:46:47,810 --> 00:46:49,526
How did Belfast go?

432
00:46:49,550 --> 00:46:52,366
My asset isn't cooperating.

433
00:46:52,390 --> 00:46:55,890
I think we have to get
creative on this one.

434
00:46:56,410 --> 00:46:58,706
She has a daughter, Emma.

435
00:46:58,730 --> 00:47:01,166
A student in London

436
00:47:01,190 --> 00:47:03,706
involved in a
radical leftist group.

437
00:47:03,730 --> 00:47:07,230
I think I can see where
you're going with this.

438
00:47:07,850 --> 00:47:13,291
We have to be very careful about
sanctioning this kind of operation.

439
00:47:39,520 --> 00:47:41,656
Yep, that's her in the pink scarf.

440
00:47:41,680 --> 00:47:44,016
Do I have to wait for her to act up?

441
00:47:44,040 --> 00:47:46,116
No, just go get her.

442
00:47:46,140 --> 00:47:54,140
Fine, but there's an
obstruction in a public highway.

443
00:47:59,190 --> 00:48:02,690
If you do not get up and move
right now, you're liable for arrest.

444
00:48:02,930 --> 00:48:04,966
Why don't you go and
do something useful,

445
00:48:04,990 --> 00:48:08,490
like arrest the fucker?

446
00:48:10,470 --> 00:48:12,246
I'm not threatening you, miss.

447
00:48:12,270 --> 00:48:15,770
Well, OK,
you should try being where I am.

448
00:48:16,070 --> 00:48:16,926
That's a threat.

449
00:48:16,950 --> 00:48:18,006
It's a threat to me.

450
00:48:18,030 --> 00:48:19,086
I'm being reasonable.

451
00:48:19,110 --> 00:48:21,446
I'm not raising my voice
in the way that you are.

452
00:48:21,470 --> 00:48:24,970
I don't care.

453
00:48:28,750 --> 00:48:29,686
Right, that's enough.

454
00:48:29,710 --> 00:48:33,210
Have a month. Thank you.

455
00:49:06,090 --> 00:49:08,286
You're in very serious trouble, Emma.

456
00:49:08,310 --> 00:49:10,726
You're in very serious trouble.

457
00:49:10,750 --> 00:49:14,310
We have four witnesses who saw you
throw the bottle at the police officer.

458
00:49:14,311 --> 00:49:16,846
We have four witnesses

459
00:49:16,870 --> 00:49:20,370
who saw you throw the
bottle at the police officer.

460
00:49:21,590 --> 00:49:23,366
What bottle?

461
00:49:23,390 --> 00:49:24,466
What are you talking about?

462
00:49:24,490 --> 00:49:26,606
Nobody was throwing anything.

463
00:49:26,630 --> 00:49:28,966
You didn't even ask about the officer.

464
00:49:28,990 --> 00:49:30,326
She was badly hurt.

465
00:49:30,350 --> 00:49:32,026
I didn't throw any bottle.

466
00:49:32,050 --> 00:49:34,646
The officer's going
to lose her right eye.

467
00:49:34,670 --> 00:49:36,886
She's going to lose her right eye?

468
00:49:36,910 --> 00:49:38,646
Since you didn't ask?

469
00:49:38,670 --> 00:49:42,170
Just a young
woman doing her job.

470
00:49:42,870 --> 00:49:45,826
How does that make you feel, Emma?

471
00:49:45,850 --> 00:49:48,306
You're making this up.

472
00:49:48,330 --> 00:49:50,986
So fuck right off.

473
00:49:51,010 --> 00:49:52,866
And I want a solicitor.

474
00:49:52,890 --> 00:49:55,586
I have a right to a solicitor.

475
00:49:55,610 --> 00:49:58,786
You can call your mother.

476
00:49:58,810 --> 00:50:02,310
You can call your mother.

477
00:52:02,970 --> 00:52:06,470
Oh my god!

478
00:52:11,130 --> 00:52:13,526
I wasn't expecting
you until next week.

479
00:52:13,550 --> 00:52:16,106
Well, It was Kalita's birthday,
not her name.

480
00:52:16,130 --> 00:52:19,630
What an art she has. What an art.

481
00:52:20,970 --> 00:52:28,970
She was like this when I found her.

482
00:52:30,500 --> 00:52:34,000
She's still alive.
I've called the paramedics.

483
00:52:43,360 --> 00:52:46,860
Bianca, we've got a serious
problem with your students.

484
00:53:03,870 --> 00:53:04,846
She collapsed.

485
00:53:04,870 --> 00:53:06,266
They think It's a cardiac issue.

486
00:53:06,290 --> 00:53:09,186
They've stabilised her.
They think she's going to make It.

487
00:53:09,210 --> 00:53:12,226
I'm the accompanying officer.

488
00:53:12,250 --> 00:53:15,566
Emma, hang on, OK?

489
00:53:15,590 --> 00:53:19,090
You're going to be all right.

490
00:54:27,760 --> 00:54:30,236
What's happening?

491
00:54:30,260 --> 00:54:31,956
She's arrested.

492
00:54:31,980 --> 00:54:33,776
I'm going to shock her.

493
00:54:33,800 --> 00:54:37,300
Let me help.

494
00:55:53,520 --> 00:55:58,900
If a friend or a foe Only
someone that you know

495
00:55:59,520 --> 00:56:03,540
Disappears from the soil of this field

496
00:56:04,520 --> 00:56:09,820
Then only then will you
know That a version of yourself

497
00:56:10,260 --> 00:56:14,040
Will fade away and never reappear

498
00:56:17,100 --> 00:56:20,600
Whatever It is, whatever you say

499
00:56:22,000 --> 00:56:26,120
When It hurt to reach
out here To make amends

500
00:56:27,560 --> 00:56:32,581
Running out of time Out
of time for a thought set

501
00:56:32,800 --> 00:56:36,700
I swore my love to the very end

502
00:56:37,390 --> 00:56:40,890
Out of time for a thought set
